Greetings from a socially distanced beach, where the fun of swimming and lounging in the sun hasn't been tainted by someone a few centimetres away ğŸ˜… Rona, stay away. Summer vacays are a treat and we want them to stay. â €
â €
A little PSA on swimwear, sharing this because A) I love when people share their choices and why, and B) swimwear is hard! I'm not someone who can get something online and feel confident it's going to fit well and look good. Bigger bust, no one size fits all for bottoms, has to be durable material because I bloody love being in the water rather than beside it... There's a checklist.
â €
The last few years I've usually opted for high waisted bikini briefs or a lower banded bikini top to dress for my shape. â €
â €
Dressing for your shape doesn't necessarily mean covering it either. Dressing for your shape is knowing what makes you feel good and why. â €
â €
A higher waist or a lower banded top are the most flattering for my shape and fabulously larger thighs. They're becoming more common now which is wonderful, if you've got any reccos for decent swimwear I'm all ears ğŸ‘€ğŸ‘€â €

description:
â €
First time I got on a road bike I was wearing a ski jacket, lime green hand me down helmet from circa 2000 movistar days and refused to use the clip ins unless I was on the grass or holding onto a fence. â €
â €
The second time, I nervously pedalled out on the road wearing a combination of old team kit (after being told point blank the ski jacket wasn't going to cut it) and vocally questioned why there was so much damn lycra involved. Most of the time my hooves remained unclipped. â €
â €
The third time I just about didn't go because I'd convinced myself road cycling wasn't for me and I was quite happy on my town bike. Skinny tyre road bikes involved too much faff. Couldn't make sense of the watts, didn't feel comfortable going fast, hated being clipped in and I felt like the other cyclists could all see I was a fraud. â €
â €
Confidence on a bike ebbs and flows whenever you're starting out on something new. I spent a lot of time worrying about my level and what others would be thinking when, in fact, the only person that it actually mattered to was me. â €
â €
If you're starting out, keep pedalling. â €
â €
The kit, the clothing, the bike, the level you're at... None of it matters to anyone but you. Every single pedal stroke is you moving forward, figuratively and literally ğŸ¥°

description:
A Gentleman and a Scholar
Husaini Zulkifly, Senior Manager of Global Sales

Husaini earned a scholarship from a Malaysian telecommunications company to study A Levels and engineering in the UK. In 2003, he joined Royal Selangor as an account executive, providing gifting solutions to large KL-based companies. 

â€œWhen I first joined, I was very lucky to be trained by our Director then, the late Mrs MK Chen, whom we all called Datin Chen. She taught me how to talk effectively to customers, craft design proposals and manage customersâ€™ expectations. Most importantly, I learnt how to balance Royal Selangorâ€™s design capabilities with client needs. Her guidance propelled my professional development,â€ he says.

The more he learnt about bespoke design, the more he enjoyed it. His clients include ExxonMobile, Brunei Shell Petroleum as well as sporting events such as the Asian Games and the CIMB Classic, Southeast Asia's sole US PGA Tour-sanctioned  golf tournament.

â€œBespoke is about craftsmanship and creativity. Itâ€™s about marking a special moment with something rare and beautiful," he explains. 

â€œWhen a bespoke order is successfully completed and delivered to a satisfied client, I feel elated. I love the moment when the client has that broad smile when he or she sees the actual piece which was previously in sketches. I get a sense of achievement when they let me know how much they appreciate my efforts. It motivates me to keep going,â€ he says.

â€œOne of my most special bespoke projects was making Formula 1 trophies for Malaysia and Singapore. We worked hard to develop a beautiful perfectly-proportioned trophy that was easy to hold. When Bernie Ecclestone, the CEO of Formula 1 back then, complimented us on the trophy design, it was the proudest moment of my life,â€ he adds.

Today, Husaini is the Senior Manager of Global Sales. His work takes him around the world, to exotic locations in the Middle East and Indonesia, meeting up with Royal Selangor's distributors and bespoke clients.

Future at Hand
Don & Nazri
Pewtersmiths, Manufacturing Department

Don & Nazri do many things together. They went to the same school as kids. They both love listening to indie music and indulging in delicious mamak-style food. Today, they work at Royal Selangor as lead assemblers for BE@RBRICK, a collaboration with MEDICOM TOY. Before being chosen to work on these collectible figurines, both Don and Nazri were taught the art of pewtersmithing by Zainal, their senior. Since then, they have created a style of their own. Their passion for pewter crafting is matched by a deep appreciation for Malaysian design. â€œWorking with pewter means learning the basics well, being patient, persistent and creative. Itâ€™s a lot like playing music. You learn the chords and practice. Then youâ€™re able to play something that is your own,â€ says Nazri, an avid guitarist whose favourites include The Beatles and contemporary indie pieces. "As Malaysia is made up of many different cultures, it is a rich source of inspiration and local pride. The products we create are enriched by designs from local arts and crafts such as batik and songket fabric,â€ explains both Don and Nazri proudly.

Work has its ups and downs and having a friend around makes a difference. â€œWeâ€™ve known since we were small school kids. So, weâ€™re comfortable with each other. We meet for lunch and talk, share ideas and experiences,â€ says Don.

Nazri adds, â€œI love being here because everyone is open to ideas and is willing to embrace change. Aside from that, I get to work on something cool like BE@RBRICK.â€ â€œI feel a sense of accomplishment when I see my work out there, admired by BE@RBRICK fans everywhere....and even on Hypebeast!â€ adds Don.
